I&#39;m not really sure what happened, but I just kind of stopped buying comic books.<br />
<br />
Then I found out about torrents.  Now I download comic books and read anything that sounds interesting at all.  For free.  I probably read 10+ comics a week. <br><BR><font size=1>07:36 01-16-2008</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' valign='top' bgcolor=#C3E3FF><img src='/global/images/premium_icon.gif' border='0' hspace='1' vspace='1'></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#C3E3FF><font class="bfont"><B><a href="http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=106">Nitsuj™</a></B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#C3E3FF' ><font class="bfont">Hmmmm....<br />
<br />
My first comic was probably an issue of Marvel&#39;s Transformers, like issue 7 or 8 - the one where Ratchet is the last autobot, and recovers the Dinobots, and tricks Megatron into thinking that the Dinobots destroyed Shockwave.  That comic doesn&#39;t even have a cover any more, I read it so many times as a kid.<br />
<br />
My first superhero comic was an issue of Action Comics, back in 1990-91ish.  It had Curt Swan on art, which was a special treat, since he was off Superman for some time at that point and had come on for a story arc.  I had no idea at the time, I just bought it because I had 75 cents burning a hole in my pocket and I was a the pharmacy near my house and it was on the magazine rack.  After that I started regularly picking up Action Comics, Spiderman Titles, and Batman titles titles.<br />
<br />
2 to 4 years later I dropped all Marvel titles, so I could keep up with the 4 superman monthlies and 3 batman monthlies as well as the other handfull of DC books I was getting into.  Why did I choose DC over Marvel?  Well, Superman was dying, Batman was broken, Green Lantern was going crazy, it just seemed like the stories were higher in scale.  My last Spiderman titles were the Amazing Spiderman arc that had the return of his parents - I got out prior to the reveal that it was all a trick from Red Skull.  So, yes that means I dropped Spiderman right before the Clone Saga, which was Marvel&#39;s attempt at telling a huge story with Spiderman like DC did with Superman and Batman.<br />
<br />
Silver Surfer and Fantastic Four were the last two titles I bought from Marvel, hanging onto them for  and additional 6 months or so.<br />
<br />
in 1996, I completely got out of comics.  and stayed out until I heard about this thing called Identity Crisis.... ugh, now I&#39;m back, and it is such an expensive hobby. <br><BR><font size=1>07:25 01-16-2008</font><BR><BR><A HREF="http://www.swccgpc.com/forums/viewtopic.php?t=15483"> Play SWCCG?  Please participate in the 2007 SWCCG Census </A></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' valign='top' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><img src='/global/images/premium_icon.gif' border='0' hspace='1' vspace='1'></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B><a href="http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=3300">Shadow 13™</a></B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">the one that kicked off my current comic book collection: ultimate fantastic four TPB #1.<br />
<br />
the first ever: 2-pack Death of Superman special at like walmart or something, which didn&#39;t even have the actual issue he died in. <br><BR><font size=1>23:50 01-15-2008</font><BR><BR><hr><img align="right" src="http://www.decktech.net/memberimages/3300rst.jpg"><br>Ryan French<br>Rebel Strike Team founder<br><i>"I&#39;m a total whore for torture porn."</i> - Patrick Sullivan</TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#C3E3FF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#C3E3FF><font class="bfont"><B>sithborg279</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#C3E3FF' ><font class="bfont">I forget, but I am pretty sure it was a Marvel team up that featured Ghost Rider and the Thing. <br><BR><font size=1>23:03 01-15-2008</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>ANIMALVADER1</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">I own thousands of comics. Most I love, some more than others, but I’ll always have a soft spot in my heart for the 1st book I ever picked out and bought myself. The book was:<br />
<br />
<br />
The Uncanny X-Men #202<br />
<br />
<img src="http://i103.photobucket.com/albums/m135/animalvader1/uncannyx-men202.jpg"><br />
<br />
Publication Date	February 1986<br />
Publisher	Marvel Comics<br />
Language	English<br />
Format	Comic<br />
Age	Modern<br />
Color	Color<br />
Country	USA<br />
Cover Price	$0.75<br />
<br />
<br />
To be clear, this is not the first comic I owned or read. I’ve had around 20 random Spider-Man, Batman, G.I. Joe, etc. given to me over the years prier to this, but I still remember vividly where and why I bought this. I was 8 years old when I wondered into the Hall of Heroes store at the mall. I first went in there with my Mom in tow with the hopes of conning her into buying me a toy I saw in the window. As I wondered around the store, I saw the wall of comics and walked up to have a look. As I stood there taking it all in, I saw it. There, at perfect eye level, in the bottom right hand corner of Uncanny X-Men #202, no more than an inch high, was Wolverine cutting the crap out of a giant robot’s leg. Even though I never read an X-Men comic before, I knew who Wolverine was because of the Secret Wars action figure I had that would always slaughter my G.I. Joes. All thoughts of the toy I originally wanted left my mind as I ran it to the counter and bought it with my allowance. I must have read it twice in the car on the way home and, I’m happy to say, I still have the issue filed neatly in a box with the rest of my X-books. Thus began my almost obsessive addiction to comics that still thrives to this day…<br />
<br />
<br />
So I ask you: What was the first comic you remember buying yourself, with your own money, and why did you buy it?<br />
